    ViewData["Title"] = "How to Build an Emergency Fund That Works";
}

<!DOCTYPE html>
<html lang="en">
<head>
    <meta charset="UTF-8" />
    <meta name="viewport" content="width=device-width, initial-scale=1.0" />
    <title>@ViewData["Title"] - FinanceCalc</title>
    <link href="https://fonts.googleapis.com/css2?family=Inter:wght@400;600;800&display=swap" rel="stylesheet" />
    <style>
        body {
            font-family: 'Inter', sans-serif;
            margin: 0;
            padding: 0;
            background-color: #f5f8fa;
            color: #333;
            line-height: 1.7;
        }

        .container {
            max-width: 800px;
            margin: 1rem auto;
            background-color: white;
            padding: 3rem;
            border-radius: 1.5rem;
            box-shadow: 0 20px 40px rgba(0,0,0,0.05);
        }

        h1 {
            font-size: 2.5rem;
            font-weight: 800;
            color: #1a202c;
            margin-bottom: 1rem;
        }

        h2 {
            font-size: 1.5rem;
            color: #2d3748;
            margin-top: 2rem;
            margin-bottom: 0.5rem;
        }

        p {
            margin: 1rem 0;
        }

        ul {
            padding-left: 1.5rem;
        }

            ul li {
                margin-bottom: 0.75rem;
            }

        .highlight {
            background-color: #edf2f7;
            padding: 1rem;
            border-left: 4px solid #4299e1;
            border-radius: 0.5rem;
            margin: 1.5rem 0;
            font-style: italic;
        }

        img {
            max-width: 100%;
            height: auto;
            border-radius: 1rem;
            margin: 2rem 0;
            box-shadow: 0 10px 20px rgba(0, 0, 0, 0.05);
        }

        .footer {
            text-align: center;
            font-size: 0.9rem;
            color: #888;
            margin-top: 3rem;
        }
    </style>
</head>
<body>

    <div class="container">
        <h1>@ViewData["Title"]</h1>

        <img src="/images/emergency.png" alt="Emergency Fund Illustration" />

        <p>Life throws unexpected curveballs — job loss, medical emergencies, urgent car repairs. The best defense? A strong emergency fund. It’s your financial safety net, and without one, even minor surprises can turn into major crises.</p>

        <h2>What Is an Emergency Fund?</h2>
        <p>An emergency fund is a dedicated pool of money for unexpected, urgent expenses. It’s not for vacations, new gadgets, or shopping sprees. Think of it as insurance that you control — and that you can access immediately.</p>

        <h2>How Much Should You Save?</h2>
        <p>The golden rule is 3–6 months of basic living expenses. That includes:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Rent or mortgage</li>
            <li>Utilities</li>
            <li>Groceries</li>
            <li>Transportation</li>
            <li>Minimum debt payments</li>
        </ul>
        <p>If your expenses are €1,500/month, your goal is €4,500–€9,000. Start small if needed — even €500 can make a difference.</p>

        <h2>Where to Keep It?</h2>
        <p>Put your emergency fund in a separate high-yield savings account. It should be:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Easily accessible</li>
            <li>Separate from daily spending</li>
            <li>Earning at least some interest</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Avoid locking it in investments — you need quick access during emergencies.</p>

        <h2>How to Build It</h2>
        <ul>
            <li><strong>Automate deposits</strong> — treat it like rent.</li>
            <li><strong>Use windfalls</strong> — tax refunds, bonuses, birthday money.</li>
            <li><strong>Cut waste</strong> — direct savings from cancelled subscriptions or habits into the fund.</li>
            <li><strong>Set challenges</strong> — try no-spend weeks or cooking-only months.</li>
        </ul>

        <h2>When to Use It?</h2>
        <p>Only for true emergencies:</p>
        <ul>
            <li>Job loss</li>
            <li>Car/home repair</li>
            <li>Medical bills</li>
            <li>Emergency travel</li>
        </ul>
        <p>Avoid dipping into it for “I deserve this” moments. Protect it fiercely.</p>

        <div class="highlight">
            <strong>Final Thoughts:</strong> An emergency fund provides more than money — it gives you peace of mind. It's the difference between panic and plan when life doesn’t go as expected.
        </div>

        <div class="footer">&copy; 2025 FinanceCalc. All rights reserved.</div>
    </div>

</body>
</html>
